Australia strongly opposes Japanese plans to expand whaling in Antarctic waters due to concerns of piracy accusations under the Antarctic Treaty.
Prime Minister John Howard criticized Japan's decision to increase whale harvests but opted for diplomatic measures over interception.
The International Whaling Commission banned commercial whaling in 1986, yet Japan continues under the guise of scientific research.
Australia's efforts to stop the slaughter face legal hurdles, with concerns over diplomatic relations with Tokyo.
Green Party leaders in Australia and New Zealand consider consumer boycotts against Japan.
The battle against whaling intensifies as New Zealand explores legal action to protect endangered whales.
